{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17584370","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17584370"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T07:44:25+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T07:44:25+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14454"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14454","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14454"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.26,0.43,0.14,0.14]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7149"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"60244"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7149","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7149"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14454"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"45664"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"29"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4906"},{"type":"tags","id":"4907"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"17067"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17157"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"60244","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/60244"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following abnormalities most frequently occurs in patients with infective endocarditis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Roth spots","Janeway lesions","Splinter haemorrhages","Osler\u0027s nodes","Petechiae"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EIn patients with infective endocarditis, \u003Cstrong\u003Epetechiae\u003C/strong\u003E are the most common cutaneous manifestation, occurring in up to 50% of cases. Petechiae are small (1-2 mm), round, red-purple spots caused by microvascular emboli or capillary rupture. Whilst they are a common sign, they are not specific to infective endocarditis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other options are less common manifestations of infective endocarditis:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERoth spots\u003C/strong\u003E are retinal haemorrhages with pale centres, seen in about 5% of cases.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EJaneway lesions\u003C/strong\u003E are non-tender, erythematous or haemorrhagic macules on the palms and soles, occurring in about 5% of cases.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESplinter haemorrhages\u003C/strong\u003E are linear bleeding under the nails, seen in approximately 15% of cases.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOsler\u0027s nodes\u003C/strong\u003E are painful, raised lesions on the fingers and toes, present in about 10-25% of cases.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThese signs are caused by various mechanisms, including immune complex deposition, septic emboli, and vasculitis. While all these signs can be associated with infective endocarditis, petechiae remain the most frequent cutaneous manifestation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Petechiae are the most common cutaneous manifestation of infective endocarditis, occurring in up to 50% of cases.","Other signs of infective endocarditis include Roth spots, Janeway lesions, splinter haemorrhages, and Osler\u0027s nodes, but these are less frequent."],"references":["Ashley EA, Niebauer J. Cardiology Explained. London: Remedica; 2004. Chapter 10, Infective endocarditis. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK2208/","Yallowit